</span>
</p>
<p class='talk-transcript__para'>
<data class='talk-transcript__para__time'>
11:17
</data>
<span class='talk-transcript__para__text'>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='666000' id='t-666000'>But there are solutions to the free-rider problem.</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='668000' id='t-668000'>It's not that hard a problem.</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='670000' id='t-670000'>In fact, nature has solved it many, many times.</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='673000' id='t-673000'>And nature's favorite solution</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='675000' id='t-675000'>is to put everyone in the same boat.</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='678000' id='t-678000'>For example,</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='680000' id='t-680000'>why is it that the mitochondria in every cell</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='683000' id='t-683000'>has its own DNA,</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='685000' id='t-685000'>totally separate from the DNA in the nucleus?</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='688000' id='t-688000'>It's because they used to be</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='690000' id='t-690000'>separate free-living bacteria</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='692000' id='t-692000'>and they came together</span>
<span class='talk-transcript__fragment' data-time='694000' id='t-694000'>and became a superorganism.</span>
